  "slug": "scotch-pie",
  "title": "Scotch Pie",
  "subtitle": "A hot water crust double pie filled with seasoned minced mutton or lamb, distinctive for its collar lid",
  "excerpt": "The Scotch pie is a Scottish institution: a round double-crust hot water pastry pie filled with highly seasoned mutton mince, with a distinctive collar that sits proud of the lid. They are eaten hot at football grounds, at New Year, and as a daily lunch staple across Scotland.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Traditional Scottish baking. F. Marian McNeill, The Scots Kitchen (1929): mutton pie method. Traditional Scottish baker's practice, Glasgow and Edinburgh variants.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The Scotch pie has a defining structural feature: the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "collar",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr4d130000s0v40fengmm1"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ". The hot water crust walls are formed about 3 cm taller than the filling level, with the disc lid sitting inside the walls rather than on top. This creates the distinctive rim above the lid that a Scotch pie fan will recognise immediately.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The traditional filling is ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "mutton",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr4d200001s0v48vkqjrtr"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " mince, heavily seasoned with nutmeg, mace, and pepper. Lamb mince is the standard substitute; use whichever you can find. The pies are eaten hot, often with a layer of baked beans tipped into the collar.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What you need",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
