      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the hot water crust",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Sift ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{plain-flour}} of flour",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " into a bowl. Melt ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{lard}} of lard",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " with 125 ml of water, bring just to the boil, and pour into the flour. Stir quickly and turn onto a floured board. Knead for 1 minute until smooth. Keep warm by covering with a bowl while working.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Form the pie cases",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Divide the dough into 4 pieces. Reserve a quarter of each piece for the lid. Use the remaining three quarters to mould a cylinder 8 cm in diameter and 6 cm tall, using the base of a glass jar as a former if needed. The walls should be about 4 mm thick. Place on a lined baking tray. Mix the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{mutton}} of mutton mince",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " with the grated onion, ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{mace}} of mace",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{nutmeg}} of nutmeg",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", pepper, filling salt, and the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-beef}} of stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Pack tightly into each case to 1 cm below the rim. Roll the reserved dough into a disc and set it inside the walls as a lid. Brush with beaten egg.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C (180°C fan). Bake for 40-45 minutes until golden all over. A probe pushed through the lid should read 75°C in the filling centre.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Work quickly while the pastry is still warm. Keep it covered between pieces.",
              "cause": "Pastry cooled too much before moulding, becoming brittle",
              "symptom": "Pastry walls are uneven or collapsing"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use mutton or lamb mince with at least 15% fat. Add the stock to the filling and mix well.",
              "cause": "Insufficient fat in the mince, or no liquid added",
              "symptom": "Filling is very dense and dry"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Aim for a consistent 4 mm wall. A small crack at the collar is cosmetic only.",
              "cause": "Pastry was too thick and baked unevenly",
              "symptom": "Collar cracks at the top"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use baking paper to line the tray; this is normal for a hot-water-crust pie with a fat-rich filling.",
              "cause": "Fat from the mince leaks through the base during baking",
              "symptom": "Pies slide on the baking tray"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The Scotch pie is as Scottish as haggis and as quotidian as a sandwich. It is the pie eaten at Hampden Park, at Hogmanay supper tables, and from paper bags outside baker's shops in Glasgow and Edinburgh on a cold morning. To eat it properly is to eat it hot, with the collar filled with something that contrasts: beans, mash, or just the cooking juices.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  "glossaryTerms": [],
